    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "79b7187f_b2b5a164",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 766,
      "author": {
        "id": 8223
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-03-24T05:18:55Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m not sure whether you\u0027re arguing for or against that IND7 is redundant. I agree thant IND7 could be checking a different prevFrame than the one IND4 checks. But I think that your example does not trigger IND7:\n\nFrame #0 is independent, by IND1.\nFrame #1 is independent, by IND4 (its prevFrame is frame #0, which is kRestoreBGColor and independent).\nFrame #2 is independent, by IND4 (its prevFrame is frame #1, which is kRestoreBGColor and independent).\n\nI think that IND7 is impossible to trigger. Proof by contradiction: suppose that frame #K is deemed independent by IND7, on examining a prevFrame #I. Triggering IND7 means that frame #I must be kRestoreBGColor and, in particular, not kRestorePrevious.\n\nTriggering IND7 but not IND4 means that the prevFrame must have changed between checking those two conditions, from frame #J to frame #I, for some ((I \u003c J) \u0026\u0026 (J \u003c K)). The only way prevFrame could change between IND4 and IND7 is by the walk-prevFrame-backwards while loop around IND6. That loop must have only walked over dependent frames (starting with frame #J and walking backwards), otherwise IND6 would trigger.\n\nIn other words, frames #I+1, #I+2, ..., #J inclusive must all be dependent frames, assuming that the \"const int prevRequiredFrame \u003d prevFrame-\u003egetRequiredFrame\" line cannot jump over independent frames: frame #30 cannot have a required frame of #10 if frame #20 is independent. This list is non-empty, as (I \u003c J), so frame #I+1 must be dependent.\n\nBut frame #I+1 being dependent means that it cannot satisfy IND1, IND2, IND3, or IND4. Its prevFrame (at the time of checking IND4) must be frame #I, since frame #I is not kRestorePrevious.\n\nHere is the contradiction: frame #I is the prevFrame when checking frame #I+1 for IND4, and it is also the prevFrame when checking frame #K for IND7. The same frame cannot both fail IND4 for #I+1 and pass IND7 for #K.\n\nWDYT?",
      "parentUuid": "ed859140_85472263",
